The Prague Stock Exchange fell to minus at the end of trading
After a sharp fall in the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange corrected losses.
Transactions with <0xC4><0x8C>EZ shares have reached almost half of the normal day-to-day business.
The Prague Stock Exchange has been following its Monday decline since the start of trading on Tuesday, when it fell by almost six percent.
This time, the fall is due to the fall in stocks on Wall Street.
In our country, too, there is a reaction of the market to the result of the vote of the US House of Representatives, which refused to support the plan for stabilization of the financial sector there.
Falling stocks in Asia
Stocks in Asia experienced a dramatic fall on Tuesday, although indices eventually wiped out some of the losses over the course of the day.
The Hang Seng index of the Hong Kong Stock Exchange depreciated almost 4% during trading, but later erased some of the losses and reduced the decline to about 2.5%.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index, which tracks the movement of Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong stock exchange, fell by 3.8 percent, with markets closed in Shanghai.
Stocks on the Sydney Stock Exchange were losing more than five percent, but in the end the losses fell to 4.3 percent.
Taiwan's stock market fell 3.6 percent, according to the Taiwan Stock Exchange Index.
“The timing of the U.S. bailout is uncertain and will affect financial markets around the world,” said Joseph Yam, Hong Kong’s chief monetary officer.
Hong Kong, although part of China, determines its monetary policy independently, i.e. without dependence on the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as in the United States.
Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd said U.S. lawmakers should quickly return to talks and approve a proposal to support the financial system.
Other countries are also at risk of being affected.
The Bloodbath of American Stocks
The U.S. House of Representatives on Monday rejected a plan to support the financial system, which was to spend up to $700 billion.
The lawmakers ignored President George W. Bush’s call to back the plan.
According to Bush, the plan would address the root causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
U.S. stocks experienced a bloodbath on Monday, and major stock indices saw their biggest fall in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones index fell by almost 7% and fell to a similar extent the last time in 1987.
The index had already fallen before the vote, but once it became clear that the motion had failed in the House, the index found itself in a free fall.
Congress backs down: U.S. government could pump $700 billion into banks
The top representatives of the US Congress and the government of President George W. Bush agreed on a broader form of agreement on financial assistance to the US financial system.
The vote on it will be held at the beginning of next week.
U.S. lawmakers have made a breakthrough in talks to approve a bailout in the form of $700 billion in financial aid to the U.S. financial system.
But it has not yet been won.
Congressmen have to finalize some details of the deal before they can release the final version of the bill and vote on it.
The financial system support plan will be discussed in the House of Representatives on Monday.
Barney Frank, chairman of the House Committee on Banking and Financial Services, told Reuters on Sunday.
According to the sources, the Senate could vote on the plan first on Wednesday.
According to economists, the announcement that the rescue plan will be approved should be the first significant psychological factor for the recovery of financial markets.
Then, however, there will be a "sobering up" due to the complexity of the mechanisms by which to help the markets to achieve it in practice.
Paulson: The Plan Must Be Effective
“We have made great progress.
We have resolved our differences on what the shape of the package to stabilize the market should look like,” Nancy Pelosi, a Democrat, told Bloomberg.
He said the final vote could take place on Sunday.
Representatives of lawmakers met with US Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson on Sunday night to give a definitive shape to the government fund.
It should buy out non-selling mortgage assets from financial companies, which drag financial firms into heavy losses and threaten the stability of the entire system.
“We are on the verge of a definitive agreement on a plan that will work and must also be effective in the market.
The recovery plan still needs to continue, but I think we’re there,” Paulson said.
A signal for Asian trading
The global financial crisis is hitting stock markets, which are falling sharply.
According to Nevada Democratic Senator Harry Reid, lawmakers are seeking a final deal in Congress as early as Sunday.
They are trying to reassure investors from trading in Asian financial markets, which are the first time the Congressional decision could affect Monday’s trading.
However, it is still unclear when the two chambers of Congress will vote on the bill, or whether negotiations at the last minute may be stuck on some problem.
Lawmakers hope it will be approved in the next few days.
However, the law still recognizes a number of changes.
The total amount earmarked for aid to the scheme is to be divided into two parts.
The initial $350 billion is to be made available as soon as possible, as President George W. Bush has demanded.
But Congress may block the release of the remaining amount if it feels that the program is not performing its function, in a succession of another $100 billion and later the final $350 billion.
Bush praises progress in talks
The President may veto the decision, but Congress may override his veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program, which was to get funding to buy bad mortgage securities, the value of which has fallen because hundreds of thousands of Americans are unable to repay their mortgages, remained.
"We've worked everything out.
“The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday and the Senate on Monday,” Republican Senator Judd Gregg said in a statement.
US President George W. Bush is also pleased with the progress of the negotiations.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, said Bush was pleased with Saturday's progress and appreciated "the two-party effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy".
Limitation of Gold Parachutes
The chairman of the Senate banking committee, Christopher Dodd, the chief negotiator, said lawmakers had agreed on responsibilities for the money program, protecting taxpayers from losses, closing relief, and timing of the plan’s funding.
The new law also aims to limit the so-called golden parachutes for directors of companies participating in the program and establishes a committee to oversee the fund.
It should be run by the Treasury Department.
“We have worked very hard on this and made great progress towards an agreement that will work and be beneficial to the market and to all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also includes assistance for homeowners who have problems with repayment.
The government should negotiate new instalments for the mortgages it buys in order to reduce monthly instalments costs for borrowers and allow them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
According to David Mark, chief economist of Patria Finance, the proposed plan is a good idea, but it will be very difficult to implement.
"And that's because we don't know what mechanism and at what price the problem assets will be redeemed.
This will determine how the financial sector and the government share the losses," Marek told iHNed.cz this week.
Whether the plan is approved now or early next week is not so important, according to Mark.
"It is much more important that this week the congressmen agree that they support this plan and that they will dedicate it as soon as possible.
The psychological significance of the agreement on approval is the most important at the moment," Marek stressed.
Duel on the edge of the knife: MP3 players against mobiles.
We advise you how to choose
While almost every mobile phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make a phone call.
It seems clear from this that it is better to buy only a phone.
Still, there are plenty of reasons to buy a separate player.
The choice depends entirely on the method of use and the claims of the future owner.
It’s probably hard to get a high-end expensive turntable at home to listen to Maxim Turbulenc’s latest album.
On the one hand, such music products do not come out on LPs, and from a qualitative point of view, there is no objective reason for this.
However, if your shelves are packed with vinyls with art rock, jazz or blues, you probably dream of such a turntable at least.
It is the same with music on the road, that is, music compressed, simplified - music in MP3.
There are also price and quality categories.
For some, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, just as a Pink Floyd fan probably will hardly try headphones for twenty crowns from the market.
Two extremes, between which there is enough space for everyone.
The choice is wide.
It also determines the battery life.
Some high-end music players can do much more than just play music, but what most mobile phones don’t happen to do.
No current device is as versatile as a phone.
In addition to the primary functions, calling and texting, it can play music and video, record both, it has a better camera, a worse camera, and maybe it can even navigate.
And when you consider smartphones and communicators, you'll have a small computer in your pocket.
It's a little miracle, because no refrigerator can grill and no TV can take pictures of anything.
The versatility of the mobile also has its disadvantages.
The more functions you use on your phone, the sooner the indicator on the display sends you to the charger.
And playing music is one of the biggest eaters of energy.
Few mobile phones can play music for more than ten or twelve hours, usually much less.
In this regard, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
For low-cost mobile phones, expect that they won’t play for more than a couple of hours.
If you still call in here and there, get another charger to work for sure - this also applies to more expensive devices.
With MP3 players, you will not have this problem, even the worst ones will last at least 9 hours of continuous operation on a single charge.
Another problem arises when recording music on a mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have a universal USB connector, and moreover, not every one of them can be directly connected to a computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly on a memory card, but few card readers can handle miniature memory cards used in mobile phones without any reduction.
You don’t need any special software for iPods, except for the exceptions.
Just fill the device with music via USB from the computer.
Most mobile phones and players already create a music library sorted by the name of the artist, album name, genre or user rating.
Some devices display only the directory tree structure similar to Windows Explorer, and some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with an operating system).
Players are easier to use, mobile phones are more capable
When choosing a specific device, pay particular attention to the battery life, memory capacity, quality and type of audio output and, of course, the comfort of operation.
If your music is primarily a backdrop and you listen to it every day only briefly, for example, in the tram, you just need any mobile phone that plays MP3.
This is something that almost any mobile phone can do.
You don’t even have to watch too much what music formats your mobile or player can do.
MP3 can handle all and the vast majority of the music that gets to you will be in this format.
It is one of the most widely used and in addition to it, the vast majority of devices can also handle music in WMA format.
There is less AAC (the format used by Apple and its iPods).
Better mobile phones also make it possible to buy music online, for example.
It is enough to visit the relevant pages of the operator (or another provider) via the mobile Internet and buy the song or album.
This service could already be a powerful argument for the acquisition of a music mobile.
Unfortunately, the offer of operators is miserable and is usually limited to fast-paced radio hits.
Prices are also not the lowest.
However, it is generally assumed that this way of selling music (whether via GSM, Internet or wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry their phones around with them.
Whenever you feel like listening to something, you can feel the phone in your pocket, while the MP3 player lies forgotten at home.
However, it still depends on whether you also always carry headphones or at least a wired handsfree.
If not, you can use the integrated speaker, which has almost every mobile phone, but only a minimum of MP3 players.
Probably the biggest advantage of music mobiles will be the price for many.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than $3,000.
For three and four thousand crowns you will already get a very decent walkman.
However, in most cases, you will be limited by the lack of output to ordinary headphones.
The best and technically most equipped phones, even with a 3.5 mm jack for ordinary headphones, cost up to fifteen thousand.
The advantage of the players is, among other things, easy operation.
The simplest - not necessarily the cheapest (see our selection) - players can be controlled by anyone.
The minimum of functions, the similarity of control with a previously conventional cassette player or even a turntable is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of a mistakenly turned on mobile Internet and consequently a huge data transfer bill.
Which device to use
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for removable memory cards (type M2, microSD, etc.).
Even with the purchase of the appropriate card, you can fit into two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
For basic models, only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB are supported.
Only the most expensive ones can handle 8 GB memory cards.
If you already have a mobile phone and want to buy an inexpensive MP3 player, reach for Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you do not have to spend more than CZK 1,100.
If you are a more demanding listener, go for specialized mobiles - walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokias and Samsungs).
These devices have separate control buttons for MP3 and the comfort of the operator is so close to a separate MP3 player.
The farthest away in the industry is Sony Ericsson, whose mobile phones from the Walkman series have the same user interface as the separately sold MP3 players.
The same service and in the same price category up to four thousand crowns, but with more memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (usually 15 hours, a maximum of 35 hours), MP3 players will take you away from the above mentioned brands.
The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Possibly
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite advanced and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
Still, we are missing something here - a virtual operator that would force the classic ones to be cheaper.
Maybe he won't be gone long.
We have written many times on Mobil.cz about the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was confirmed by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, who pointed out that the price of SMS in our country is higher than in the rest of the Union.
After the recent steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation may arise - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are held so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that would really want to get into the fight.
It may sound paradoxical, we have three mobile networks and a penetration rate of over 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to praise the fact that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
This is often emphasized by the Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunication Office (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99>ák, who in the past has repeatedly expressed that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a classic operator with its own network probably does not have much of a chance (after all, it would probably be difficult to find frequencies).
But there is another option - a virtual operator.
It was the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that brought a significant reduction in prices, to which even classical operators had to respond.
Even before the introduction of Tesco Mobile and Virgin Mobile, similar voices were heard in the UK.
But it turns out that the place for such operators is and can be really successful.
We don’t have to go too far for examples.
In February of this year, we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, the operator has managed to attract more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator there.
At the same time, Mobilking is backed by the financial group Penta, which owns U:fona in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to be able to work effectively, they need much fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They do not entail relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
In the world, virtual operators are usually profiled as low-cost - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often balanced by a narrower range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half the price of its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, even a bet on a fresh target group can be quite a good move.
This service is specifically aimed at men.
“The right guys choose Mobilking – an operator they like and can trust,” says David Seibertz, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which runs the virtual operator.
It is difficult to say if a similar concept as in Poland could be caught up in our country.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for the segment approach on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated in terms of service offerings."
In the Czech Republic without a chance, say mobile operators
But it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look very promising.
Rather, Mobilking will be launched in other countries in our region," Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>ková, a spokeswoman for Penta, said in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, it confirmed that existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not in favour of this idea.
Rather, they are trying to do everything possible to prevent any potential competitors.
The interest in launching a virtual mobile operator has not been hidden for a long time by the GTS Novera group, which would like to take the next step towards becoming a real competitor of O2 Telephones in the field of corporate customers.
"We are very interested in being able to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunication services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already made progress with some of them," said Pavel Kaidl, spokesman for the group.
Maybe he's flashing for better times.
From unofficial information, it seems that the first virtual operator should be waiting perhaps by the end of the year.
For now, however, its creation is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment, we do not believe that there is room on the Czech market for the emergence of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
So far, we have not been approached by any entity with a complex and serious project in this area," said Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> from the O2 Telephony Press Department in his statement to Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová adds in rare agreement with O2: “We have not yet seen any viable and mutually beneficial business project on which to build further.”
He added: “It’s hard to see a virtual operator on the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
At this point, we would have to have a concrete agreement on the table in order to be able to think in this short term.”
Vodafone is focusing more on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> says: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of cost-sharing and infrastructure.
This is what we consider to be the most beneficial for our customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for fast mobile internet.”
Responsible authorities - with operators one hand
The progress of mobile operators is easy to understand, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to a decrease in prices and, consequently, a decrease in their profits.
So why make it easier for such a competitor?
The fact that operators are able to pull a rope when something is at stake is also evidenced by the quarrels around the formation of U:fon.
Probably the biggest pressure towards <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> was at the time of the creation of U:fon by T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the CTU website.
But now U:fon is a good argument for not admitting a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová commented: “The competitive environment of the mobile market has recently been enhanced by the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of another player would place high demands on him and, above all, on his services."
However, given this approach of mobile operators, the complete disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is directly striking.
It is not just the CTU's position, which unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike the UK and other developed countries - does not have the power to interfere in competition.
They belong exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
But he took his typical position on the whole issue.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after the conclusion of a contract between the mobile operator and the virtual operator to lease the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, as the offer of potential candidates was probably not interesting enough for classical operators," said Kristian Chalupa from the Department of External Relations of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS in response to our question.
From the representatives of the operators, the statements thus formulated are not likely to surprise.
This is more than a weighted one from an authority that is supposed to represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, ensure that no one abuses their position on the market.
Especially when Kristian Chalupa adds: "Abroad, where virtual operators normally operate, we can observe that their entry into the market contributed to lower prices for mobile phone services."
However, the pressure on the correct functioning of the market environment and the fall in prices are not in the interests of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
What is truly shocking about the whole case is the touching convergence of the three mobile operators, which follows from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really a coincidence is entirely self-evident.
Just like the exact same price of gasoline at gas stations, it is certainly only the work of chance and fierce competition.
"The Office has not found any signs of anti-competitive conduct in this case and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position and therefore does not have the corresponding increased responsibility for their actions in the market.
The necessary tools for opening up the mobile market for virtual operators are likely to be lacking in the telecom regulator as well," Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of a dominant position in the market is one of the many points of contention.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets carried out by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, according to which telecommunications is a single market in terms of competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
Some legal experts, however, offer a different view - to create a virtual operator, the consent of the network operator is always required.
And the mobile operator - quite logically - has a monopoly on its network.
So in a certain segment, it must necessarily be dominant.
Even if we do not accept this argument, it should be a minimum warning for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that the three mobile operators are acting strikingly similarly.
At the same time, the complaints of a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in dealing with all operators.
Claiming responsibility to the CTU is a fairly common trick in telecommunications, with which the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS keeps its hands off the whole matter.
We’ve met him on several similar occasions.
Unfortunately, the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act did not succeed in enforcing the extension of CT<0xC3><0x9A>’s powers to competition in telecommunications, despite the fact that many experts had promised to improve the situation.
This must be more than well known to the representatives of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS, but apparently their interests are elsewhere.
It goes when no one's looking
At the same time, the functioning of some pseudovirtual operators, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies that issue their own price lists of mobile phone services, which, however, are only partially public.
This is usually done by multi-level marketing companies.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only the chosen ones.
The magic lies in the fact that the company faces the operator as a classic business customer who orders a large number of SIM cards.
As a significant customer, he will then receive special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If there are cases that you are talking about, it could be a violation of the terms and conditions that we would deal with and could result in the termination of cooperation with the company," Martina Kemrová replied to our question on this issue.
However, it is quite unlikely that such activity would not reach the responsible people from mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three mentioned companies, there may be thousands of customers.
None of the operators are opposed to such a procedure.
They make significant profits from the activities of these companies and, unlike real virtual operators, they do not threaten them in any way with their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> draws attention to possible problems: "The law allows similar speculation, but only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
In addition, they must accept that the SIM card in their phone is not in their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it as regular customers of mobile operators.
This is what should be at least weird.
In addition, another question for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS opens up.
If mobile operators close their eyes to a similar procedure, why are they blocking the emergence of a virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has quite strong powers to detect similar activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the explanation of the operators that they have no idea about this and their business conditions prohibit it.
When we won't be the most expensive
As mentioned several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought a noticeable drop in service prices.
At the same time, in virtually all countries where virtual operators were created, classical operators tried more or less to prevent their emergence.
The arguments they used were practically the same - too small, perhaps too saturated market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In developed countries, however, it was at these moments that regulators intervened, defending not the interests of mobile operators, but their customers.
Whether through formal measures or informal pressure, the first virtual operator was created and more were added to it.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory authorities dismiss the whole case as a hot potato.
From our experience, we can not get rid of the impression that the ambiguity in competences is more than suitable for them in these cases.
But let's not throw the flint in the rye.
If the behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator is really coming soon, the Czech mobile market may move again.
If one of the operators admitted the emergence of a virtual mobile operator, it will hardly be possible for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And we may stop calling it more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
