Even rats have feelings.
When a rat or cockroach runs from danger, does that mean they feel fear too?
Neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux believes that many animals have feelings.
But how can we verify whether they feel the same way when they behave like us?
The online journal "Edge" has been publishing contributions from well-known scientists for several years.
SPIEGEL ONLINE in its series presents selected answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have feelings and other states of consciousness that I or anyone else has not yet been able to prove, when we cannot even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope, because all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, as soon as we begin to focus on another kind and open up questions of perception or general consciousness, we enter into impassable terrain, because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it will do the same as many other animals: pretend to be dead, flee or attack.
Humans behave similarly, from which some scientists conclude that there are comparable subjective experiences.
I don't believe that, though.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to that of animals.
This is because the circuits associated with human consciousness almost always include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its contribution to short-term memory and execution or control functions).
This vast region is much more developed in humans than in other primates, and it seems to be completely absent in other creatures.
At least for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, among them knowing who we are and being able to plan and make decisions, there is reason to believe that man is even different from other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity could be concealed by the linguistic essence of a person: because so much of his perception is associated with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, we can exclude animals.
But even if the consciousness of language did not matter, it would certainly be influenced by language, so that animal consciousness, however constructed, would probably differ from most states of our consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to know what consciousness looks like in other animals.
When, as something internal and subjective, it can neither be measured nor, due to special hardware, analyzed on the basis of our own experience, we are faced with great problems in exploring it.
Most of my inferences relate to the content of conscious experience, but besides that, there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more scientifically accessible.
It would be possible to study processes in the consciousness of animals regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happens in studies of short-term memory in primates, especially on the example of visualization.
But this approach, pursued by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, focuses more on neural correlates of consciousness than on causal mechanisms: both may or may not be identical.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the nefrontal cortex for the realization of visualization.
What does this mean for feelings?
I deduce them from the fact that the emotional system, such as the fear system, is activated in the brain conscious of its own activity.
What we call “fear” is the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as bodily reactions) makes use of operative memory.
Viewed from this angle, feelings are closely related to those areas of the cortex that are characterized by primates, and especially humans.
