Bilingualism debate: immersion in English
In this issue of Focusing on Education, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi will discuss candidates’ attitudes towards bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, an academic in California and director of education at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is the co-author of Worse Than You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs to Choose Schools.
Effectively addressing Hispanic voters is a tricky matter.
Barack Obama’s educational agenda only proves this.
Obama’s campaign notes that “African-American and Hispanic students are significantly less likely to graduate than white students,” which is true.
To combat such performance gaps, Obama’s educational agenda particularly promotes, among other things, “transitional bilingual education” for those just learning English.
The question is whether Barack Obama’s commitment to bilingual education, which emphasizes the use of languages other than English in the classroom, is not stronger than his interest in reducing the performance gap.
Take, for example, Sixth Street Prep, a charter elementary school in Los Angeles County East.
In the vast majority of cases, the students of this school are Hispanics from low-income families.
More than a third of students, many of whom have only recently arrived, are still learning English.
Nevertheless, in the state tests in mathematics in 2008, an incredible one hundred percent of fourth-grade students reached the highest level.
Ninety-three percent of fourth-grade students reached the highest level in the state tests of English language and literature.
This incredible success has been achieved by a different method than the one preferred by Obama.
Sixth Street emphasizes control and practice, constant assessment of abilities, and an approach without excuses.
Further, and that should be noted by Obama, according to Linda Mikels, director of Sixth Street, the school’s pedagogical approach for those just learning English is “total immersion.”
Immersion in English emphasizes the almost privileged use of English in teaching.
Miss Mikels, who is against bilingual education, told me, "We had a tremendous success with one brand-new student from Mexico -- after twelve months, you would walk into the classroom and not know which one it was."
"It's working," she said, "for us."
Would Obama take a school like the Sixth Street Prep as a model of what other schools with large proportions of Hispanic and English-learning students should look like?
The school’s achievements should make the answer to this question a matter of course, but its own party’s educational agenda (the National Educational Association is a longtime advocate of bilingual education) and its own consistent support for bilingual education obscure the prediction of Obama’s answer.
While Obama agrees that immigrants should learn English, he recently trivialized the matter by saying that people should stop worrying about “only English” laws.
Instead, “you should make sure your children speak Spanish,” he said.
If Obama really wants to erase performance gaps, he should think carefully about educational patterns that work rather than ridicule and trivialize them.
Oil declines sharply due to renewed economic worries
Oil prices fell sharply on Monday because of concerns that even the U.S. plan to bail out financial markets might not revive the economy.
Oil futures prices fell by up to 7% in the morning trading on the New York Commodity Exchange to $99.80 per barrel.
Prices have fallen by more than $20 per barrel since last Monday.
Over the past two weeks, commodity markets have been rocked by financial unrest on Wall Street and by a pair of powerful hurricanes in the Gulf of Mexico.
After peaking at $145.29 a barrel in July, prices fell to nearly $90 a barrel earlier this month, again leaping on the wave of enormous uncertainty in financial markets.
Anxiety again gripped investors on Monday, even after the presidency of Congress announced it had reached an agreement on the largest bailout plan in history over the weekend.
This report has been overshadowed by fresh concerns that the financial crisis is far from over.
In the latest episode of the advancing decay, the government announced that Citigroup would buy the banking division of Wachovia Corporation.
Meanwhile, the Belgian, Dutch and Luxembourg governments partially nationalized the European financial conglomerate Fortis.
Analysts at Barclays Capital said the furious weekend talks that led to the plan to bail out the economy “prove to be unable to revive market sentiment.”
As the economic situation deteriorates, demand for commodities, including oil, is expected to decline.
"The outlook for markets with global stocks, interest rates and exchange rates has been strongly uncertain," Deutsche Bank analysts wrote in a report to investors.
"We believe that commodities will not be able to escape the infection.
“From a commodity perspective, our biggest concern is the extent to which the U.S. virus will spread throughout the world, and especially to China.”
Analysts cut their expectations for next year as oil consumption declined due to slower economic growth, and cut their forecasts for gasoline prices for 2009 by about 20%.
Wild riding in the second quarter beat the team's record
After spending more time at the Jets than anyone else in the last eight seasons, defenseman Shaun Ellis thought he had seen it all.
Then on Sunday he followed the development of the second quarter, in which the Jets turned a pointless game into a spaniel ride.
"I've never seen anything like it," Ellis said.
The second quarter began after the Jets and the Arizona Cardinals leveled the grim clouds above each other with their agonizing game.
Then quarterback Brett Favre sent Laveranuese Coles to the 12-yard touchdown sprint, perfectly anticipating an afternoon in which their evolving collaboration moved miles ahead.
Favre sent Coles in this quarter for another two touchdowns, including the one in which the cornerback fell, and another 10 seconds before the half of the match.
"It was nothing special," Favre told Coles about all his passes.
“He’s a damn good player.
We communicated well, no matter what people thought.”
While Favre and Coles were throwing, the defense was attacking Cardinals quarterback Kurt Warner.
Cornerback Darelle Revis caught a stray throw and returned it 32 yards to the touchdown.
Safety Eric Smith picked up another pass and caught it.
Linebacker David Bowens forced Warner into a fumble.
The last loss of the ball, the fumble Bowens forced, was perhaps the best ever.
The Cardinals got to the ball 10 seconds before the end, and after the Jets got the ball back, Jay Feely kicked a 20-billion-dollar goal out of the field, taking the lead 34-0.
That's the most the Jets have ever won in a quarter.
Jets coach Eric Mangini, when asked to describe the madness, said, "The second quarter, or the third quarter?"
When he was told that both - the Jets allowed 21 points in the third quarter without an answer - Mangini said: "I can tell you that I enjoyed the second quarter much more than the third.
There were a lot of points in a short period of time.”
The rested Gebreselassie improved his world record
Haile Gebreselassie of Ethiopia once again showed why many consider him the best long-distance runner ever when he broke his own world record in the Berlin marathon on Sunday and became the first person to run a 26.2-mile race under two hours and four minutes.
Winning on a pleasantly flat track in 2:03:59, he beat his previous time of 2:04:26, which took place last year in Berlin, by 27 seconds.
Gebreselassie, 35, has set the 26th world record of his career, which is really incredibly wide - he broke the world record or at least is the world champion at all distances from the metric mile to the marathon.
Last month, Gebreselassie skipped the Olympic marathon in Beijing because he feared — perhaps too frightened in retrospect — that air pollution would irritate his asthma problems.
Instead, he promised to run in Berlin.
In almost perfect conditions - sunny and 48 degrees at the start, 55 degrees at the finish line - Gebreselassie won Sunday with a lightning fast average of 4 minutes and 43 seconds per mile.
Since track runners such as Gebreselassie and Paul Tergat of Kenya focused on longer tracks, the marathon record for the past decade has fallen by more than two minutes, since Ronaldo da Costa of Brazil won in Berlin in a time of 2:06:05 in 1998.
After Sunday's victory, Gebreselassie told reporters he had calf cramps two weeks ago and missed a week of training.
Apparently, the pause woke him up rather than delayed him.
"I'm so happy," Gebreselassie told reporters.
"Everything was perfect.
I started over a week ago and I was a little doubtful today, but everything was fine.”
He has also been criticized - especially in Kenya, Ethiopia's East African rival - for over-planning his races, generally avoiding the world's top marathon races, relying on drivers as if it were a race on the track, and setting world records above the sense of competition.
But this criticism can hardly reduce Gebreselassie’s enormous running qualities.
Maintained at a pace of four Kenyans, Gebreselassie reached half in 1:02:04.
After the drivers fell off, Gebreselassie was constantly chased by two elite Kenyan runners, James Kwambai and Charles Kamathi.
A little before three miles before the goal Gebreselassie last took and escaped Kwambai, who then ran in second place in 2:05:36, improving his personal maximum by almost five minutes.
Kamathi finished third in 2:07:48.
In the women's race, Irina Mikitenkova, a native of Kazakhstan who is now a German citizen, finished an excellent year with the seventh fastest time in history 2:19:19.
The record time of 2:15:25 is held by Paula Radcliffe from Great Britain.
The 36-year-old Mikit<0xC4><0x9B>nková won the London Marathon in 2:24:14 last spring.
She skipped the Beijing Games due to what was described as a back injury, but recovered and won in Berlin, and in the third marathon she ever ran, she improved her personal maximum by almost five minutes.
She ran the race cleverly and deliberately: she let four Ethiopian and Kenyan runners escape in a big lead and then dragged them out after about 18 1/2 miles.
Askale Tafa Magarsa from Ethiopia finished second in 2:21:31 and Helene Kiprop from Kenya finished third in 2:25:01.
The Pride and Obstacles of Black Lives in a Separate City
Hidden among the sprawling amusement parks of the larger Orlando, a few miles from everything shiny, noisy and gigantic, lies a quiet city where the pride and demands of African-American life come to life.
Eatonville, the first completely black city to be incorporated into the state and where Zora Neale Hurston spent her childhood, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: "a city of five lakes, three croquet courts, three hundred brown skins, three hundred good swimmers, plenty of kwajawa, no schools."
It is now a pilgrimage site.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to Eatonville's annual Dawn! festival to pay tribute to Hurston, Harlem's most famous female writer of the Renaissance.
The city she described remains aside, though she made it a stop for tourists by including it in a Florida tourist guide created by the Federal Writers Project during the economic crisis.
It is still as independent, dignified and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted and did not share their true feelings with a white man who "knows so little about us that he doesn't even know what he's missing."
Even today, in a year in which the black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, calls for an open discussion of races, many residents remain wary of the views of others.
“We pay a lot of attention to how our story is told,” says 59-year-old Hortense Jones, who has lived here since birth and is a member of the oldest parish in the city.
"It has to be right."
Eatonville has long been characterized as a paradox of triumph and effort.
It is both a historical model of black ascension and a community of nearly 2,400 people where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a center of literature, but also an oak-shaded example of Southern rural black culture - sometimes despised, sometimes praised - that arose from American slavery.
Not surprisingly, the locals are both proud and protective.
And worries about the idea of Eatonville really started with Zora, which is the only way Hurston is called here.
She introduced her hometown to the world through heartfelt books full of dialects such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
The five paragraphs of the Florida Tourist Guide turned the city into a shortcut to Highway 17, which runs through Florida’s often-missing downtown area, into a stage of black history and human drama.
With the bang of the big drum in her life and literature, Hurston led her readers to the shop of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clark, and then turned to more personal places.
"On the left side of the road," she wrote, "there is a white-brown-decorated modern national school with well-maintained courtyards and playgrounds that Howard Miller always takes care of, even though he can't read or write much."
She also mentioned Dash’s new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn “sells drinks of all kinds and anything that fits an hour-long hotel.”
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston linked Eatonville to self-government, but also illiteracy, remarriage, and sex.
This was clearly not a typical Fodor's publishing house.
In fact, it wasn't a portrait that everyone would appreciate.
"Zora said it the way it was," says Ella Dinkins, 90, one of the Johnson Girls choirs who made Hurston immortal by quoting men who sang obscene songs about their beauty.
"Some people didn't like it," she added.
Hurston is still remembered here as a chipper eccentric, who often returned after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Seventy-seven-year-old Augustus Franklin recalls that most of the time, when she landed in the city, she arrived unannounced in a huge Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants in a city that is still proud of its dignified dress.
Most residents were fascinated, Franklin said, but many were sneering.
"People have always been happy to see Dawn," Franklin said.
But, he added, swinging on a chair on the back terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, “she never stayed too long.”
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were removed from the press.
Eatonville and the rest of the world seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had previously lived.
There were no major funeral ceremonies or large public readings in Eatonville.
"I don't think they understood her meaning for the world or her legacy at all," said Valerie Boyd, author of Hurston's 2003 biography Wrapped in Rainbows.
The change came in the 1980s.
Orange County officials wanted to run a five-lane highway through the city instead of Kennedy Boulevard, the local two-lane main road.
Orlando's rampage has already pushed Interstate 4 through the western edge of the city.
The proposal came at a time when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult historical period.
Forced integration, along with other things, ended the relatively idyllic isolation of this community.
In the 1950s, the race-mixing struggle brought hatred to the doorstep of the community.
"At that time, a bunch of white guys, they came and threw oranges and stuff at the people who sat on the side," Franklin said.
"Actually, we had a lady here who was killed by it.
They threw a watermelon out of the car."
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's demand for forced integration and said its decision in Brown v. the Education Chamber was "offensive rather than glorified to my race."
Residents now claim that school desegregation, although positive in some areas, has reduced cohesion in Eatonville and undermined the courage of local youth.
"The Negro children were used to hugging - I remember that - you hugged your teacher in the morning, you hugged your teacher in the evening," said N.Y. Nathiri, daughter of Elly Dinkins and executive director of the nonprofit group Preserve the Eatonville Community.
This continued until teachers and students came from the same place, she added.
"You're not hugging your white teacher because your white teacher -- I mean, there's a cultural barrier," Miss Nathiri said.
Civil rights, however, helped create space for many more Zora Neale Hurston - black writers, actors and artists who, like her, rose above prejudice with frivolous self-confidence and quotes such as "How can anyone deny the pleasure of my presence!
I don't understand."
In 1975, Alice Walker traveled to the unmarked tomb of Hurston and began fighting to revive her reputation.
Five years later, a celebrated biography of Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway came to the shelves of bookstores, re-introducing it into the American canon.
The project with the highway arrived just as Eatonville’s most famous daughter found the lights of the ramps again.
The Hurston's former neighbors now considered her a savior.
To show what it can do with its highway, the community began planning the Hurston Festival in 1988.
Thousands of fans arrived for the inaugural event two years later, and every January many return for the celebration.
After a few years, the state withdrew from the highway proposal.
"These five highway streams resurrected, you'd say, a real civic pride," Nathiri said.
Boyd put it simply: "Zora saved Eatonville."
Victory over the motorway project helped change the image of the city.
Out-of-towners like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who started attending the church in 1993, began to appear in larger numbers, and residents began to rethink the past.
Eatonville joined the National Historic Register in 1998.
The new one-storey library (named after Hurston, of course) was opened in 2006 on the re-asphalted and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: just six miles from downtown Orlando, it can sometimes act like a downed alley in summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded with just 27 black families in the 1880s.
(Nowadays, 90 percent of them are black.)
Strangers who come looking for the story and meaning of Eatonville are still often treated with caution.
Permission for most interviews is required in advance, and certain things — like wall paintings in the oldest Eatonville church painted by whites and depicting blacks in the fields — are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Jones, a bold, confident teacher who likes deep red, still fear that their isolated community will not be properly understood.
And even as Hurston’s festival grew, so did domestic pride.
Especially young people tend to see Eatonville the way Hurston saw her entire race: beautiful, troubled, and so on, but not better, not worse, and as proud, creative, hardworking, foolish, and diverse as other American races and ethnicities.
From the voice of Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, there is a sincere love for the village as he plans to return to Eatonville after college to work for the local government or the police, which he says would benefit from some help.
And even younger ones, such as the 11-year-old twins from Winter Park, Alondra and Alexia Kenon, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people, when they pass by, think, 'Uh, this town is nothing compared to the others,'" said Alondra Kenon recently after church.
"But if you really stop and look at history for a while, it's a very nice city."
Here in New York, we're all fluent in finance.
At first glance, nothing has changed.
If tourists in Manhattan had stayed away from the newspaper stands and the huge TV screens in Times Square, they would not have realized they were standing in the middle of a storm.
They would never guess that in the glazed beehive of offices above their heads, every day the bankers and investment fund managers who monopolize New York have the worst “bad day in the office” since the 1929 crisis.
The messengers still roar metal carts on the sidewalks and carry the muffin bakers to breakfast meetings.
Hispanics still move between the towers and wear, like human mules, fifty ironed shirts hanging from the pendulums on their backs.
Office rats are still queuing for their morning bagel at the street food stalls, and it's still not possible to get a yellow cab between four and seven in the afternoon on a weekday.
It didn't look like a crisis at all until, with all the talk of pessimism, I decided to open a savings account on Thursday afternoon.
Even though I had timed this assignment to cover the late afternoon siesta at my local branch of JP Morgan Chase, there were already about twenty people waiting in line.
Not in front of cash desks to pick up or deposit cash, but in front of a counter where older clients order checkbooks, tourists ask for a way to Macy’s mixed goods store, and new customers open accounts.
Most of the people before me, as I learned from Starr, my “licensed personal banker,” came for the same reason I did.
But they have already taken their savings from smaller banks in places like New Jersey, Pennsylvania or Staten Island.
They have withdrawn money from so-called thrifts (slightly similar to building savings banks), money associations, and those types of savings banks whose branches operate only in one state, which claim to care for their customers as a family.
Over the past year, 15 such banks have quietly gone bankrupt.
A few days ago, Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion in assets, went bankrupt, and as New Yorkers returned home for the weekend on Friday night, another bank, the Wachovia, with $440 billion in assets, tried to catch a rescue buyer.
The office and shop workers who stood in front of me, fearing another collapse, were transferring their cash to a bank that is perceived as a safe haven and that does most of the rescuing on Wall Street.
Ordinary New Yorkers have learned fluent financial language over the past week.
A woman in my local Chinese supermarket was talking on the phone to Lehman Borthers, that bankrupt bank, and to her slender chief executive, Dick Fulda, with such familiarity as if she were gossiping about a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the uniformed, about 50-year-old housekeeper of my apartment, changed the subject of our ordinary conversation -- Brad, Angelina, or my grocery delivery.
After my visit to the bank, she told me, "I now have my savings in money market funds.
I moved it, I won't take any chances."
Muslim tombs desecrated after Austria's right-wing crack
Heinz-Christian Strache, on the left, of the Austrian right-wing Free Party, and Filip Dewinter of the Belgian right-wing Vlaams Belang party, are attending a rally in Antwerp on Thursday 17 January 2008 to present the organization "Cities Against Islamization".
They carry signs similar to traffic signs, showing mosques crossed by a red line.
Police accuse right-wing extremists of desecrating a Muslim cemetery in Austria on the same weekend that far-right parties made huge gains in general elections.
More than 90 graves at the Traun cemetery near Linz were severely damaged sometime between Friday evening and this morning, and police are convinced it was an organized action.
The culprits sprayed Jewish symbols on some graves, such as the Star of David, but the detectives are convinced that it may have been an attempt to disguise the motives of extremists driven by hatred of Muslim immigrants.
It is unclear whether this incident was in any way linked to the election.
A spokesman for the Muslim community said they were "deeply shocked" by reports of defilement as the Muslim fasting month of Ramadan drew to a close.
In the meantime, Austria is entering the round of searching for its own soul after the right-wing collapse in yesterday’s parliamentary elections.
The two far-right parties, which together garnered more than 30 percent of the vote, the Free Party and the Alliance for the Future of Austria, led a vehement anti-immigration campaign and some of their slogans were condemned as xenophobic.
Heinz-Christian Strache, the chairman of the Free Party, which received over 18 percent of the vote, protested against scarves and burqas in the campaign and even expressed his opposition to foods that are perceived to be related to Islam.
At his last meeting with voters in Vienna, he spoke of a "European brotherhood" to prevent the rise of Islam.
Both sides are trying to ban the construction of mosques and minarets, arguing that they are political symbols of the ongoing Islamization of Austria and Europe.
Polls and analyses carried out immediately after the elections, which put the far right in the position of the strongest political bloc in the country, suggest that this change was caused mainly by young voters who are worried about their future in the European Union.
Gary Glitter is not allowed to travel abroad.
Gary Glitter, a glam rock star who was convicted of child sexual abuse, has been barred from traveling to France and Spain.
Officials imposed the six-month ban on Glitter after he informed monitoring authorities that he planned to travel to Spain via France.
The Kent Police Department approved the travel ban last Thursday after handing over evidence of Glitter’s past convictions for child sexual abuse to officials.
Glitter, his own name Paul Gadd, did not attend the hearing at Ashford's lowest criminal court in Kent, but was represented by lawyers from Corker Binning.
A spokesperson for the Judicial Service said: “On Thursday, September 25, at Ashford’s lowest criminal court, the Kent police asked for an order to prevent Mr. Paul Gadd from crossing the border into France and Spain until March 25.
Paul Gadd was not personally involved.”
Glitter, 64, has informed authorities that he wishes to travel abroad, according to his record in the register of sexual offenders.
He must notify the authorities if he wants to travel abroad for more than three days.
They must also give the planned departure date to the police a week in advance.
If he fails to inform the authorities, he could be sentenced to five years.
Kent Police have said they will not discuss Glitter's possible travels to the county.
A Kent Police spokeswoman said: "The Kent Police will do whatever is necessary to protect children in this country or abroad.
From our point of view, it is easier to track someone who stays in the UK, because we have extensive systems here that handle potential dangers more effectively.
Protecting Kent residents is a top priority for the Kent Police Department, and we are working diligently to monitor the behavior of recorded sex offenders to minimize any danger to the public.”
Glitter returned to Britain last month after spending 27 months in a Vietnamese prison for abusing two girls aged 10 and 11.
When he was released, he flew to Bangkok, where he was to board a flight to London.
But he said he wasn't feeling well, and he refused to go to London.
The Thai authorities did not allow him to pass the passport check and he eventually flew to Hong Kong.
Chinese authorities also denied him entry, and he flew back to Bangkok, where Thai police and immigration officials insisted on his return to Britain.
On August 22, he finally arrived at Heathrow Terminal 3 and stayed there while his attorney, David Corker, went to Uxbridge's lowest criminal court in West London, and at the same time Scotland Yard successfully requested a warrant requiring him to register as a sex offender.
Glitter was previously jailed in the UK for four months for possession of child pornography.
A source in the interior ministry said Jacqui Smith, the interior minister, was calm and glad Glitter was prevented from traveling to France and Spain.
"To capture the real character, I photograph the master off-stage." Günther Bauer - photographer
No heels, no calls, no costumes.
Only the essence of the great masters of flamenco, detached from the focus on interpretation - this is the only way to achieve a relaxed expression of a man or a woman.
On the one hand, an artist.
The second - a man.
Inseparable, apart from privacy, in those moments far away from the audience - then one can see a confidential gesture, the depth of a fleeting glance or the passionate gesture of hands that are carefree, because they are not going to step onto the stage.
German Günther Bauer alternates in "Flamenco-people" the theatricality of performances with singers, dancers and guitarists with the lesser-known face of the masters.
With this intention, the photographer compiles a unique iconography of flamenco from different backgrounds.
The exhibition, which takes place within the framework of the Month of Flamenco Photography (Mes de la Fotografía Flamenca), "reflects the ever-increasing international importance of flamenco", says the author, explaining that "Flamenco-people" "can be any kind of people, but if you look at the photographs, you will find that these are not typical images of artists on the scene.
These people portrayed "on the street" are artists able to bring passion, sadness, joy to the stage... and completely captivate the audience.
To capture the personality of these artists, it is not necessary to take pictures on stage.
He has his personality and character inside him.
I was interested in creating a relaxed atmosphere that would allow me to capture the personality of the flamenco giants.
Enchanted by the "Cante de las Minas" festival, Bauer began in 1997 a long journey of portraying flamenco singers, guitarists and dancers on a board camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and material, resemble classical photography.
The use of different stylistic means contradicts the classical basis of the picture and gives it a contemporary spirit, an idea that, according to Bauer himself, also reflects flamenco: "Music with very traditional roots, but which does not cease to surprise and evolve."
What attracts the audience is not the action of the dance, singing or play itself, but the personality and character of the artist.
The search for the moment when we will meet the most essential, the spirit that manifests itself in the way of perception, being and experiencing, was and is a constant of the work presented during these days in the gallery of El Fotómata.
This selection of almost seventy photographed artists is made up of well-known flamenco figures, such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales and Vicente Amigo.
The project has become a kind of anthology of flamenco and will soon receive a book edition that will contain exhibited portraits.
A passion for portraiture led Bauer two years ago to the idea of repeating the idea on "Portraits of a Sports Veteran" ("SportARTproject").
Although their concept is different from “Flamenco-people”, the photographer admits that “to photograph people, get to know them and have the opportunity for a moment, whether longer or just shorter, to enter their lives – this is my passion.
I think that in photography, portrait is the most difficult genre.
A person meets or encounters people, personalities that sometimes he does not even know, or they give him just a few minutes for a photo shoot.
Despite similar circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to realize my ideas."
The collection of portraits of contemporary flamenco called "Flamenco-people" is on display at the El Fotómata Gallery in the street de la Mata 20, parallel to the Alameda de Hércules, and can be visited until 16 October.
