Interview - Blood That Is Sure Again
Hema-Québec celebrated its tenth anniversary yesterday and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice as Hema-Québec has become one of the most reliable and efficient blood suppliers in the world.
Above all, he regained the confidence of the public, which was seriously shaken after the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is well known, the national blood reserve administered by the Transfusion Department of the Canadian Red Cross was contaminated with the Immune Deficiency Virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In view of this drama and the wave of public unrest, the Canadian Government launched a public inquiry in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, aimed at explaining the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and formulating recommendations to prevent such a disaster from happening again.
While Judge Krever delayed submitting the report, some provinces put in place a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, Gélinea’s committee held this role.
Following Gélineau's and Krever's reports, two contractors were established in Canada: Héma-Québec, which was to administer Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Company for the supply of all provinces and both territories.
"When Héma-Québec started its activities in 1998, only 38% of people still had confidence in the Quebec blood system," Dr. Décary recalls.
"The situation was depressing.
Through continuous efforts to increase the safety of blood products and continuous work in this area, we have regained public confidence over the next years," he says, adding proudly that at the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of the Quebec population already trusted Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary, however, does not lose sight of the fact that "trust is something very fragile".
Since its founding on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
"At that time, we saw many cases in Europe of the human form of mad cow disease, a new variant of the disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease," says a woman who has led the company since its founding in 1998.
"And we didn't know if this disease could spread through the blood.
We have therefore relied on one of the basic recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau report, according to which, if we do not know it and if a serious disease, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, is at stake, which is characterized by brain degeneration inevitably leading to death, exclusionary measures should be taken.
Thus, in April 1999, we rejected blood from people who had stayed in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
A few years ago, it was safely proven that this disease is transmitted by blood.
So this episode showed us that adhering to the precautionary principle made sense."
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting the HIV virus appeared on the market: nucleic acid (NAT) tests, which allow to detect the presence of the virus itself in donor blood, and not the presence of antibodies on which the tests were based previously.
NAT tests have made it possible to shorten the deaf period that occurs between the moment of infection of the patient and the moment when our techniques can detect the first viruses in the blood, explains the specialist.
We were able to shorten this period to less than a week.
We have substantially reduced the risk that some donors could be infected without knowing it and without being able to figure it out.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of acquiring AIDS through blood transfusions.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of getting HIV-contaminated blood.
In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone gets infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Québec distributes 400,000 to 500,000 blood products annually, it will take 24 years for the first case of HIV transmission through the blood product to occur.
I believe that today we can receive or prescribe the blood transfusion necessary for healing in complete peace," said the head of the management of Hema-Quebec.
“The challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know what pathogens may appear in the system.
Just last year, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted into the blood by insect bites.
We must always be cautious,” Dr. Décary continues, stressing that in addition to a safe supply, Héma-Québec must also count on a sufficient supply.
“Needs are growing as the population ages.
As a result of more aggressive cancer treatment, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has implications for the blood donor network, which on average consists of only 3% of Quebecers eligible for donation.”
Every healthy person is at least 18 years old, meeting the eligibility criteria, but can donate blood only once every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer blood are not accepted because they have AIDS or malaria, and if they have visited a country where mud fever is rampant, they are excluded for one year.
“With this 3%, we can maintain a state that meets the needs of hospitals.
Deficiencies are very rare.
Members of the donor network, however, need to be supplemented in proportion to how they age and can no longer donate blood.
However, it is difficult to persuade people to donate blood, especially to keep them and encourage them to become regular donors.
“Life is so unbridled today that we rarely find an hour to donate blood,” said Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissue, such as bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin that is almost exclusively used for major burns.
These tissues are analysed, processed and frozen before being deposited at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public umbilical cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord, formerly considered biomedical waste, abounds in blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our thousandth umbilical cord blood sample into the bank, and we expect to collect over a thousand per year.
At the beginning of next year, we should start offering them for transplants," says Dr. Décary, who describes the cord blood collection program as very popular.
"Some moms are disappointed that they do not have access to it," because Héma-Québec does not have enough funds to offer this comprehensive and expensive program to all hospitals in Quebec.
