In the September 17 issue, Le Devoir printed a letter from Patrick J. Garver, executive vice president of Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
With Orwellian logic, he confirms that the world’s largest gold producer has launched a lawsuit against three authors and a poor little publishing house for insults to honour, with the aim of sparking “transparent public debate” and demanding six million.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge truthfulness, especially in the case of prosecutions for offense to honor, but the law.
It is not surprising that Garver completely ignores this crucial distinction.
Or is the best way for Barrick Gold to lead a public debate is to bankrupt anyone who dares to defend the opposite position?
Whatever the outcome of the trial, the authors and publisher of Noir Canada will be forced to spend respectable sums to be prepared to defend themselves and fight in a very uneven battle against an army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets of a mining company.
The tactic in these unbalanced battles, after all, often consists in ruining defendants in order to enforce a conciliation procedure that will shut the mouth of the opposing party and, moreover, frighten anyone who dares to commit to this matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it should have presented its view of the matter to the public.
Contrary to what is happening in the few countries where Barrick Gold operates, in Canada, the debate is normally about exchanging ideas and not about stick wounds.
Thus, mining companies were not enough to open their books, their documentation, and establish a real debate through newspapers, media, publications, and the funding of independent scientific teams that could bring light to the matter.
However, Barrick Gold seems to have no confidence in public opinion and swiftly rejects petitions and letters in support of the authors of Noir Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can demand "public debate" while contemptuously disregarding the views of the same public?
In the vice-president's world, this word seems to refer only to well-paid lawyers, and not to all Canadians; this is a rather narrow concept of the term.
In a democracy, people have the right to speak up.
Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - that the public, who supports the authors and publishers of Noir Canada, does so primarily because they reject the brutal ways of the mining society.
The public is ready to hear Barrick and judge the matter, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, not in what many perceive as a prosecution, in which the defendant is to be silenced (as part of its prosecution of the "public debate" Barrick, incidentally, has just filed an official call for the authors of Noir Canada to use this term, to re-announce the authors of the...
Aside from Garver’s surreal speech, the prosecution initiated by Barrick Gold is a direct attack on the university’s freedom to research and seek the truth that is essential to any democratic society.
In general, he denies the right to cite credible sources and to debate the facts and interpretations that constitute the very basis of intellectual activity.
If it is impossible in a country like Canada to study and discuss topics that the rich companies of this world do not like without being subjected to repeated prosecutions, who else will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted public and transparent debate, it could have created it if it had followed the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
He's entitled to an answer.
The university environment to which we belong has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s exaggerated lawsuit clearly shows that, contrary to what it claims, it has no desire to have a transparent debate.
It is a loss for the university world, as it is for the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place measures to limit this type of unjustified prosecution.
Wall Street Rescue Operations: Democrats and Republicans get along
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the biggest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
A new version of the plan to use $700 billion to curb the financial crisis that has plagued Wall Street for months has yet to be approved by both houses of Congress.
In particular, it envisages: better control of elected representatives over its application, new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of deposited public money, new measures to capture the number of houses seized due to non-repayment, as well as the right to monitor the level of wages paid to managers of rescued companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi, and Senator Judd Gregg, a Republican representative at the negotiating table, announced this good news yesterday minutes after midnight, after a two-day negotiation marathon.
"We have made great progress and reached an agreement that will be effective in the markets," Bush administration spokesman Henry Paulson said in a statement.
“Everything has been done to keep the real economy and ordinary Americans safe from the Wall Street crisis,” he said.
“This is a crucial point: if we don’t do this, the trauma, the chaos, and the disruption to the everyday lives of Americans will be enormous,” said Republican Judd Gregg.
Over the last few hours, negotiations have run to maximum speed for fear of the effect that another failure would have on investors’ moods.
The time limit was the opening of the markets this morning.
Both US presidential candidates were invited to negotiate later, and both were more in favour of an agreement, but did not fail to express their dissatisfaction with the need to resort to such an extreme solution.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama credited the amendment to the agreement with some measures, in particular those aimed at allowing homeowners to keep their homes, and measures on the wages of managers of state-rescued companies.
“When we ask taxpayers to take special measures because of the irresponsibility of some people, there is nothing to congratulate.
But these measures are necessary," he explained on television.
His Republican rival John McCain, who was asked by another station if he would vote for the proposed plan, replied: "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
“The rough features I’ve read [show] that this is something we’re all going to have to digest and make it possible to move forward.
The choice of inaction is simply unacceptable,” he said.
The goal of the $700 billion plan is to buy up dubious receivables and risky and non-sellable assets of U.S. financial institutions with taxpayers’ money.
The plan comes after 14 months of crisis unleashed by the bursting of the real estate bubble, which first led to the collapse of risky mortgage loans (subprimes), then transferred to other, more widespread forms of credit (PCAA) and resulted in the freezing of cash and the collapse of banks and financial institutions.
The failure of the first draft of the agreement last week is the responsibility of Republican MPs.
Since the Democrats agreed that some of the "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty would be guaranteed by the government, but not bought, there has been a belief that the impasse has been averted.
In an effort to bring opposing views in Congress closer together, a provision was added to stipulate that the government would be able to introduce new fees to help it reclaim its deposit if it had to assume losses for five years as a result of the program.
The new plan envisages a deposit of the first amount of 250 billion, to which it will be possible to add another 100 billion, if the president deems it necessary.
A further $350 billion is to be approved by Congress in a new vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will acquire shares in the rescued companies, which will pay him dividends in case of profit and which he will be able to sell again when everything is over.
The federal government will be able to delay the procedures for the seizure of property related to the loans covered by the plan, as well as to set limits on the amount of remuneration and compensation paid to executives of the affected companies.
The drafters of the plan would like to submit it to a vote in the House of Representatives today and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all the efforts made, it is not yet certain that their plan will be green.
Yesterday, voices continued to rise against this project in both the Republican and Democratic camps.
"It's very clear that Washington can't hear you," Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, told voters.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But making money from taxpayers is not the solution.”
Democratic Representative Brad Sherman, the moderator of a group of congressmen nicknamed the "committee of skeptics", presents the whole thing differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
Four hundred distinguished professors of economics, including three Nobel laureates, wrote to us: “We ask Congress not to rush too much and carefully examine which path to take.”
At the same time, it was once again confirmed in Europe that this crisis is a global crisis.
At the end of the emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>11.2 billion ($16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was withdrawing from the purchase of its competitor, which is on the verge of collapsing since it lost <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2 billion ($2.9 billion) as a result of the risky loan crisis on the purchase of real estate in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of Europe’s top 20 banks and top 10 insurers.
"We will not lose this money," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said.
“In return, we get the right to vote and influence in the bank.
And that’s what savings and households can appreciate in today’s uncertain times.”
On the other side of the English Channel, the British government seems to have begun nationalising another bank affected by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government was to take over all existing Bradford and Bringley loans, of which more than 41 billion ($75.5 billion) were loans for the purchase of real estate.
According to its announcement yesterday, the Spanish bank Santander will buy branches and accounts of clients of the British bank.
Bradford and Bringley will be the second bank, after Northern Rock, to be nationalised by the British government since the financial crisis began.
Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Death of a Socially Engaged Icon
His beauty with azure eyes had long been his trump card, according to other weaknesses.
Has this American actor with a charming smile escaped from narcissism?
Yes and no.
The shyness, sensitivity, and relentless talent that he possessed also distanced him from the power category that breeds true stars.
But what a long-distance runner he was!
Paul Newman died on Friday at the age of 83 at his Connecticut ranch from lung cancer and remains one of the last icons of the fat years of American cinema.
Less spectacular than Brando, to whom he resembled and who had long been a rival on the screen, Newman was a more cautious actor, certainly more fragile, but also an apostle of freedom and the dissolution of dramatic conventions.
Mixed blood often produces beautiful babies.
He was born in Ohio in 1925, his father was a German Jew and his mother was Hungarian.
From these European roots was born one of the famous faces of the American dream.
No exaggerated ego, which is the last sign of quality.
Because the whole country was in love with a self-made man, a warrior wounded in battle in the Pacific War who studied acting at Yale in the early 1950s, then attended New York's Actor's Studio and triumphed in theater, television, and soon film.
The same man who fought for civil rights was also a car racer who came second at the 1979 Le Mans 24 Hours and a sex symbol, despite forming an exemplary pair with actress Joanne Woodward since 1958.
With him also go the shadowy places of this hidden, discreet, socially engaged star, allergic to the noise of his own show-business, which will forever remain to some extent mysterious.
A decent man, in the noblest sense of the word.
Paul Newman’s departure this weekend has made film lovers dizzy as his big roles compete on the black screen of memories.
After him, he parades more than half a century of the constantly changing American Seventh Art.
Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid (1969), a young man who rejects his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in Cat on a Hot Roof, a 1958 adaptation of Tennessee Williams.
From a less distant past (1990), we remember his sensitive Mr. Bridge, anxious at an advanced age by a marriage that did not meet all expectations.
So many other Paul Newmans have gone down in history.
Boxer Rocky Graziano, the abusive, violent, memorable delinquent from Somebody Up There Likes Me by Robert Wise, a role intended for James Dean, taken after his death, which in 1956 made Newman a real acquaintance.
A sympathetic gangster in the absolutely great The Sting, Oscar for Best Picture in 1973.
A bitter and vengeful billiard player in Robert Rossen’s amazing The Hustler (1961), he plays the same character in Martin Scorsese’s The Color of Money, earning him the only Oscar out of seven nominations in 1987.
This face wandering for ages, it was him.
There he is again.
In his career, different epochs compete with each other.
Young people know him mainly because of the iconic Slap Shot by George Roy Hill (1977) in the role of Reggie Dunlop, an unconventional hockey coach.
Fans met him again in 1994 in The Hudsucker Proxy of the Coen brothers.
He then ended his career as the godfather of the Irish mafia in Road to Perdition by Sam Mendes in 2003.
Unlike several film legends who left the craft relatively soon, Newman remained in the industry for a long time, although he condemned Hollywood with its gilding, pomp, and concessions.
French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier, not without humor, considered it "a lively challenge to underplaying", judging that in his performances he pushed too much on the saw.
For the beautiful Paul Newman, whose roles came as if on a tray, the profession was not always so gentle.
However, he played the first lovers less often than the outsiders: neurotics, alcoholics, loopholes and despairers, whose decay and rebellions were reflected in his perfect features.
As a director, Newman revealed little-known aspects of his shy sensitivity.
His 1968 film Rachel, Rachel (based on the novel by Canadian Margaret Laurence), starring his wife Joanne Woodward, provides a sensitive female portrait full of melancholy.
In 1984, he dedicated the film Harry and Son to his son Scott, whom he lost to an overdose, a work full of shame and sadness.
In a flurry of tributes to Newman yesterday, his great friend and former fellow fighter Robert Redford (played together in The Sting and Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid) sadly declared, "His presence has made my life and this country better."
Generosity, love of life, these are the main qualities of the deceased actor.
Aside from his legendary career, there is also a great fighter for civil rights, ecology, independent film, opponent of Hollywood’s decline.
We used to see his image on bottles of wine vinegar, sauces, biscuits and other foods, which may have seemed rather tasteless, although it was a gag at first.
However, the profits from the sale went to the account of his Foundation for Hard Childhood.
So, instead of letting himself be swayed by fame, Newman engaged in society until the last moment.
He left a letter to his five daughters with these words: “Always and until the end, your father was grateful to his happy planet.
It was an honor to be here.”
And it was an honor to be able to follow the life of such a bright-sighted and generous American artist.
And besides, after all, an exemplary citizen.
What was produced in the invoice factory of Zuschlag & spol.?
Soon, on October 8, the trial will begin in the criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his associates.
The politician and his associates are accused, among other crimes, including forgery of documents, of fraud committed by a long-term and systematic criminal organization, as a result of which exceptionally significant damage was caused.
According to the prosecutor’s office, they used the money raised in public tenders for their own purposes and often used fictitious invoices to prove the fulfilment of their tasks.
The money from the state and local governments - a total of about 65 million forints - went partly to the treasury of the organization Fiatal Baloldal, partly to the pockets of individuals.
The method also communicated by the investigating authority was that the money raised in the tenders was collected on the basis of invoices for which there was no real consideration and never met the obligations assumed by the association.
According to the prosecution, a large part of the invoices were false.
The printouts for these invoices came from the Józsefváros market, the round stamps were made in Kiskunhalas.
The names of the companies on which the production of invoices is to take place were decided, among other things, on the roundabout along the northern bank of the Balaton, which was sent by István Lados János Zuschlag.
According to his testimony, he was first named to look at pensions and restaurants.
In them, he asked for bills for his consumption, according to the model of which invoices submitted in the framework of public tenders issued by, among others, the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs, respectively, the Municipality of the capital were produced.
Most of the invoices were issued by István Lados with his partner András <0xC5><0x90>rim, who, according to our information, most often wrote the reports needed to obtain subsidies.
On his "study trip," Lados looked at a cellar.
According to two invoices issued by Zuschlag and his associates in 2003, this catering establishment provided catering for a group of ninety members of the Biztos Pont association.
However, according to the head of the company, so many people would not fit into this facility at once.
Similarly, an invoice issued in the summer of 2002 by the Jobb Jöv<0xC5><0x91>ért Foundation, later Együtt and Harmadik Évezredért, was fraught with formal and content errors.
The guesthouse in Badacsonytomaj had only three rooms, more than ten people could not sleep in it one night, yet one hundred and thirty guests were listed on the invoice.
However, the form-fillers with a rich imagination exaggerated this even when they listed on the documents a company dedicated to the same hospitality - Pigal s. r. o., in whose accounts, according to the information provided to the public prosecutor's office, documents under the names Jobb Jöv<0xC5><0x91>ért and Hoppá did not even appear.
Gy<0xC5><0x91>z<0xC5><0x91> Farkas, the head of the company, told hvg.hu that when he was summoned to the prosecutor’s office and showed him the invoices, he immediately knew that they were fake documents.
"The name of our business and our tax number were in the wrong place on the stamp."
In addition to the formalities, the fact that they accommodated 100 people according to the invoice did not agree, because they have only eleven rooms that do not have such a large capacity.
In addition, catering was also indicated on the invoice, and their restaurant has not worked for a long time.
The zealous invoicing manufacturers were also not convinced that the Budapest travel agency in question only organizes foreign trips, and the invoice with cash payment, which also did not coincide with the invoicing practice of the company, foolishly stated as a service of intermediation of travel in Hungary.
Moreover, as it emerged during the investigation, VAT was also mentioned in the document, although the organization of trips to countries outside the European Union was exempt from VAT.
Four documents issued to Jobb Jöv<0xC5><0x91>ért by Hotel Révfülöp s. r. o. did not agree, among other things, to the amount of VAT. The company’s activities are not covered by the 25% VAT, but by the 15% VAT, in addition, the hotel’s employees issued only printed invoices, but the invoice was made by hand.
In addition, the "publishers" spoiled the invoice, for example, by stating to one company, as it turned out through the investigation of the public prosecutor's office, as an activity carried out by road transport of goods, which the company originally based on investment advice did not perform.
The fact that the invoices issued by the Együtt and Harmadik Évezredért Foundation and the associations of XXI Szazadi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont are false was also revealed due to formal deviations - inconsistent invoice format and false stamp.
As in the case of Ravenna k. s. or the Kunfehértó Sports Camp, whose representatives denied that they had issued the invoices.
For example, the counterfeiters did not even notice that HIB s. r. o. from Nyíregyháza was in liquidation at the time (2001), when a group from the Fiatal Városért association was eating there, which is why, according to our information, the liquidation commissioner of the company also denied that he would issue the paper.
Invoices were issued consciously.
The second group of invoicers consists of those who knew they had to issue a fictitious invoice.
The Esély Budapestért Foundation issued accounts for about four million forints to the Harmadik Évezrédért Foundation at the request of the Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták organization.
According to the indictment, one of the defendants, Ludovic Györfi, persuaded the head of Collab s.r.o. to issue a fictitious invoice.
Biogate s. r. o., currently in liquidation, also cooperated with Zuschlag and his associates and in 2003 supplied the Jobb Jöv<0xC5><0x91>ért Foundation and the Atlasz and Vörösfeny<0xC5><0x91> associations with invoices worth about five million forints, beyond which there was no real economic activity.
Neither does the money flow, because the invoices were later cancelled, which organizations forgot to mention in their documents.
Another group of invoicing firms included those that had ties to the defendants.
Thus, for example, Ivan Kubatov was the deputy representative of the Ukrainian company Delta Trió s.r.o., dealing with fuel and motor vehicles, based in Budapest, where the company is not found.
In October, November and December 2005, the company issued several invoices for the sale of computer equipment worth approximately 18 million forints.
According to the information found by the investigation, these invoices were purchased by the Kiskunhalas company Cash Investment s. r. o., which had been in liquidation since 14 September 2005.
The director of this company was a man from Romania, to whom Iván Kubatov was to hand over documents related to the company in 2002-2005.
As we know, Kubatov admitted during the investigation that on behalf of the company he issued invoices to Atlasz, Hoppá and the Együtt and Harmadik Évezredért foundations and accepted their consideration.
At the request of Iván Kubatov, the companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari s. r. o. and Jos-Investment k. s. were founded by Romanian masons.
In fact, none of the companies worked, according to the defendant, because they did not get a job.
Nevertheless, the companies benefited him, because at the request of the co-accused lawyer Zsolt Szente, who also prepared their founding documents, he issued invoices on behalf of the companies to Atlasz and Y-Generáció associated with Zuschlaga.
On behalf of the companies Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaextrade, Kubatov gave the organizations a total of 15 invoices worth 14.2 million forints.
The prosecutor’s office concluded that Kubatov had recovered 10 percent of the amounts indicated on the invoices and VAT.
In order to issue fictitious invoices, this time for the tender for Biztos Pont, the man also used the company Szi-Beri k. t.
In January 2006, Y-Generáció and Szövetség and Modern Magyarországért submitted proposals to the public tender of the Mihály Táncsics Foundation (TMA), a public benefit organization of the Socialist Party.
They received 500,000 forints each, but did not spend the sums on the objectives set out in the proposals.
In order not to reveal this, TMA submitted five fictitious invoices from Works Team s. r. o.
These invoices were found during a search at <0xC3><0x81>rpád Kemecsei’s office at the Ministry of Education.
During the trial, some of the defendants will probably describe the course of production of invoices, as they have already done at the prosecutor's office.
It may be more interesting if the main defendant János Zuschlag himself decides to reveal everything.
His statement so far is not very detailed, and although he has promised to explain everything in detail several times, he has not yet done so.
The question is whether it is in his interest - in exchange for paying a large part of the damage, fifty million forints, perhaps the Socialists have made a deal with him and Zusi will take it upon himself.
He could have been offended, for his requests for a softening of the conditions of his detention, namely, his placement under house arrest, had not been heard until now.
While perpetrators of economic crimes who have done much greater damages that have not yet been paid can walk freely or at least wait for the end of the proceedings against them in their homes, he does not have this option.
The Psychology of Trumping: Why Do We Spend More Money?
At auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, overvalue goods.
The neurological and economic foundations of this well-known - and seemingly irrational - behavior have been revealed by researchers in the field of neuroscience and economics at New York University.
According to their study, published in the journal Science, people do not want to lag behind in an eBay auction competition, so they would rather pay too high a price.
Using an experimental auction, the research attempted to map the scheme of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers bet, the other group participated in the auction, while using the method of functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) were studied active areas of the brain of experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could win money, but during the auction, an important element of which is to beat the other side, a whole located under the cerebral cortex, called the striatum, began to function intensively during the loss.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region plays a role in the “self-reward” mechanism of the nervous system.
According to the researchers, the screwing of the price can therefore be explained by an attempt to avoid a sharp reaction of the striatum.
To support their theory, members of the research team from among economists conducted a cross-sectional financial investigation.
At the same time, three groups bid against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was simply told what the real value of the product was, and they made bets.
In addition, members of the next group were promised that if they left the game victorious, they would receive another $ 15 as a reward.
The third group received $15 before the auction, but in the event of a loss, its members also lost this money.
The difference between the two groups was, therefore, that one was highlighted winning and the other was highlighted losing.
However, members of the group playing "against losing" were willing to go higher than it was in the control and "winning" group, which confirms the hypothesis of neurologists.
"These results cannot be inferred from any pre-existing economic theory.
So far, they have explained the phenomena observed in auctions with the joy of winning and avoiding risk.
It wasn’t until neurological imaging methods helped us resolve the discrepancy between the two theories that we now came to a third explanation,” said Andrew Schotter, a professor at the University of New York’s School of Economics.
Hepatitis: when to see a doctor?
Approximately half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of domestic cases of hepatitis infection is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand of them are treated. The reason for this is that patients often do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is a collective name for infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities in their symptoms, characterized by inflammation of the liver and jaundice, but the causes of the disease and the diseases caused by them differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, depending on the causative agents of the disease, spread in two main ways: hepatitis A and E in the digestive tract (for example, infected food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
In any case, travelers should protect themselves by vaccination against the A and B viruses, there is no vaccine against the C virus.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after ingestion of an infected food, usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal discomfort, nausea.
After that, jaundice forms on the skin and whites of the eyes, lightening stools and darkening urine. Treatment can take up to two to three weeks.
Every year, a million people worldwide die from a more serious form of the disease, liver cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that it is estimated that only one in ten infected people is treated with medication.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to liver cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, the causative agent of the disease destroys the liver cells insidiously, so the first symptoms appear in many cases only in 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, carrying out regular depistage is very important.
In three groups, the disease is much more common than the average: among people who received blood transfusions before 1991, among drug users and among people with tattoos.
Currently, the estimated global number of individuals infected with chronic hepatitis C virus is 200 million.
Since the disease can be proven by routine laboratory tests, a person should contact his GP if he notices any symptoms of unknown origin.
With early detection, the disease is treatable, the virus can be removed from the body, preventing infection and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized worldwide by the organizations representing the sick in 2004.
Its purpose is to draw attention to chronic inflammation of the liver caused by these viruses, the causes of its occurrence and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Who believes in God doesn’t hurt so much?
According to the results of recent research, faith in God works as a certain analgesic that could ease the death of already Catholic martyrs.
Scientists from the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment, examining how in man the belief in the god of perception of pain affects, reported the British newspaper Telegraph.
As part of a rather bizarre survey, 12 Catholic believers and an equal number of atheists were subjected to electric shocks, while all observed a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to eliminate a large part of the pain.
Thanks to the technique of studying the human brain in detail, it turned out that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for regulating pain.
The research is the first of a series of researches, which are attended by scientists, philosophers and theologians from different parts of the university.
Precisely the test was carried out by attaching a sparkling instrument to the left hand of the subject, which produced electric shocks.
Researchers asked participants to observe two paintings: the 17th-century Virgin Mary of Sassoferrato and Leonardo da Vinci’s Lady of the Cross, painted in the 15th century.
The authors of the study hoped that the view of the Virgin Mary would evoke a certain state of piety in the faithful, while they chose da Vinci's painting because it is not very different from the first and gives a soothing impression.
The subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during this time they received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive parts, while separately watching an image with a religious or general theme.
Catholics said they felt “safe” when looking at the Virgin Mary, as if they had been “cared for” and “peace filled them.”
They said they felt 12 percent less pain when watching a painting with a religious theme than when they had Leonardo’s work in front of them.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the research, believes that a similar effect can be achieved with any highly impressive image even in atheists, only to find the right photo.
"We would have to find a picture that they would perceive very positively, from the position of a mother or father," the psychologist said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results.
“The practice of faith should change, and in many cases will change, our personality,” Wright said.
After such great results, it is only a question of what effect it would have on regulating the pain of believers if they were shown some Madonna by Leonardo or a painter of similar caliber.
Would looking at a quality Virgin Mary mean achieving even better results?
You are what you share of yourself
On his tenth birthday, Google can declare that people can find it at least as well in their pockets as in the sky above their heads; they know where they have been on vacation, what professional examinations they go to and what they are interested in.
According to Eric Schmidt, one of the company’s CEOs, this is still not enough.
However, as for the skeptics who make a parallel with the Orwellian dark vision, the very essence of the Web 2.0 is not clear to them.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google’s main goal is to collect even more personal data about users, which is necessary to enable the founders of Google to stick to their original intention, which was: “Let’s organize all the information in the world!”
According to a Google spokesperson, the company, even after ten years of world-class work, is only at the beginning to be able to work with all the information.
Asked what would happen in five years, Schmidt said he would like Google to be able to answer questions like “what should I do tomorrow?” or “what kind of work would be good for me?” – but software won’t be able to answer such seemingly simple questions until they know enough information about users.
Not all Internet users are well aware that the search words are accurately captured during the search, as well as the IP address from which they were searched and to which pages they moved after the search.
Thanks to the Personalized Search service launched two years ago, for example, users can keep a history of their surfing, they can look back at what they were looking for and what they clicked on, thanks to which in the long run, findings are generated much more directly tailored to them - the same logic will be used for the service Recommendations, through which the system will be based on the previously mentioned and saved preferences.
What if my data is used against me, what if someone looks at what I do? – asks users who are afraid when looking at Google’s data monopoly.
In most cases, the extent of the potential power represented by the company is more frightening, the counter-reaction does not evoke guilt awareness in Internet users, fear of punishment, desire for freedom or even rebellion against power.
However, it is a confirmed fact that all search terms are not only captured, but in justified cases they can also be issued to a third party, in such legal cases the personality rights of Internet users do not protect anything.
The most well-known recent example was probably the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, during which Google provided the Brazilian government with information that allowed the identification of pedophiles from the Orkut community sites established through it.
However, internet users who are concerned about personality rights could still rest in May when the company, along with the electronic rights organization EFF, successfully proved its truth in a dispute with the FBI: Google must not be forced to provide any information secretly requested by the FBI in the future by any article of the constitution.
(At the same time, the federal government has successfully won nearly 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms, which it has gained with reference to the strengthening of the Children’s Protection Act passed years ago, yet it has failed to get individual user search lists, or complete lists of websites and keywords covering a period of two months.)
The view of Google is thus quite contradictory: it is flogged by those who are afraid of providing their personal data, because they feel that their intimate sphere and private life will be harmed by starting to use Google’s services, and they oppose it with a revolt that belongs to multinational companies with a conservative image.
Meanwhile, American geek culture and its wild branch, gathering enthusiastic computer fans, activists and users, appearing in many countries, see in him a new generation of big companies, a “corporation that’s booming now”, unlike its rival Microsoft, which is considered to be the conqueror of the world because of Windows, although they both fight for the same goals.
This may be due to the fact that Google, unlike Microsoft, does not require an identification code from its users and does not want them to pay for their applications; an open, free and constantly fresh source of information and a package of programs appears to be much more accessible, youthful, "cooler" than the practice of the official software giant.
However, this may also be due to the fact that geeks accurately understand the very problematic relationship between the Internet and personality rights, which was brought with it by one of the most leaning keywords of recent years: the Web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is about nothing but cooperation, about intentionally leaving traces behind and using the communication channels we have at our disposal, and although their scope is different for everyone, the essence remains the same: we show ourselves.
The average young person can have a profile on several community pages from Facebook to Xang, which he can easily connect to other services, such as Twitter or last.fm app, recording his music, then he can connect to navigation systems such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm.
While we can read about a lot of exemplary cases, from which she lights up: a girlfriend in the morning looking at a flood of photos of mutual friends easily finds out with whom her joking friend spent the evening, or the company can fire his employee just because on his blog expresses his honest opinion about the top management completely.
One who lives an online life consists of what he shows, so we could define the basic thesis behind the behavior of today’s youth.
And anyone who wants to hide something, or at least avoid Google’s monopoly, has the option (starting with Scroogle, which uses Google’s search engine, but does not intentionally leave a trace).
For example, a large number of people do not intentionally register on community sites so that they cannot be found. Google's online applications from text editor to photo editor and news portal can be exchanged for alternative versions that are not connected to giant server parks and that do not build the best possible profile of us.
Public opinion is not secretly expecting Google to show its teeth.
With its current value of $156 billion, the company is worth more than IBM ($140 billion), Intel ($124 billion) or Coca-Cola ($110 billion), AdWords/AdSense advertising space is jeopardizing ad agency investments and services being rolled out at an ever-accelerating pace are seriously making life more difficult for not only Microsoft but also numerous other software designers.
Critical observers, however, also find counterpoints to the regime appearing to be disturbing: the top management, for example, completely rejected the protests of employees after raising the fee for the company's kindergarten to twice, at any time the daily meals of employees were too expensive, according to the management of the company, but all this is lost in the sense of a deal that their government has lost the favor in 2006.
One of the internal rules of the company is that it never advertises new medical services in advance, only when they can be used, but it is certain that the expected problems of the coming months and years can shake the world in new places: while some believe that Google's project aimed at scanning and archiving his books and magazines can take on such problems with the American system, the company can take on such a large profile with its own, that the company will soon have to deal with it.
The fact that Google is building a genetic database can then serve as a good starting material for future generations of science fiction writers, Cory Doctorow’s famous novel “Scroogled” describes, with Orwellian reminiscences, a future in which one can frighteningly well approach a person only with the help of Google data.
