Intelligent car imitates the flight of a bumblebee
What would be the best method of developing technologies capable of preventing collisions, if not imitating the detectors of obstacles found in the natural world?
Bees, for example.
The initial strategic idea of the surprising project, presented at the Japanese trade fair CEATEC, was inspired by the bumblebees engineers from Nissan. It was about how to build a new generation of systems to prevent collisions.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has developed a biomimetic robotic control system such as the BR23C, a robotic minicar equipped with the characteristics of bees, with the ultimate goal of helping to create a system that can eliminate all collisions.
“During the flight, each bee creates its own personal space of oval shape, which is actually very similar to our safety protective packaging,” explained Kazuhiro Doi, the brand’s general manager for technology PR and R&D.
An important role is played by the composite eyes, which allow bees to see in all directions at an angle of view of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the folded eye, engineers came up with the idea of a laser rangefinder.
It identifies obstacles up to 2 meters ahead of BR23C in a 180-degree field of view, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the onboard microprocessor, which instantly turns into an operation aimed at preventing a collision.
The obstacle is captured within a fraction of a second, after which the robotic car begins to imitate the movements of the bee, and turning the wheels to the extent necessary to prevent a collision immediately changes direction.
Unlike any existing system, this deflection manoeuvre takes place in an entirely instinctive manner.
“If this were not the case, the robotic car would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Ando, head of the Mobility Laboratory and Robotic Car Project.
It must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology fits the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the safety shield, within which a collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
This process should not take longer than the blink of an eye.
However, unlike bees, this movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and only in the direction in which the wheels can be turned.
Instead of the endless possibilities offered to bees when avoiding them, only the possibility of rotating, accelerating and decelerating was applied in the case of a robotic car.
BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and have a higher energy density, meaning they have a longer lifespan than lithium-ion variants.
According to Ando, the important thing is instinctive, intelligent response, not the ability to process, much less the storage of data.
This mechanism has to process and respond to only a few incoming signals per second.
It does not need to store and respond to them using intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so it constantly uses only a memory size of a few kilobytes.
It does not need memory with giga- or megabyte capacity.
This is the first step towards developing an instantaneous evasion technology that Nissan estimates could reach mass-produced vehicles within a decade.
Another application may be the connection of the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system, which, after avoiding obstacles in the way, would lead the motorist to the specified final destination.
Damn dear baby already has a name
The $700 billion bailout bill, which is to be split into several instalments and aims to buy back bad bank loans, is already in writing.
Half of the amount will be used in the first round.
After further talks, which ended after midnight Eastern Time on Saturday, congressional officials reached an agreement in a multi-day debate on a $700 billion bailout package.
"We've made significant progress," Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic president of the House of Representatives, said in a statement.
Both presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain, also supported the compromise on the package.
Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson said: "The programme will work and it will be effective, but more action needs to be taken."
The written form of the package was published before the opening of Asian markets on Sunday at 8 p.m. Washington time (i.e. at 2 a.m. CET on Monday), but it did not cause any special rise in the stock exchanges.
On Monday, the House of Representatives will first vote on the draft law on the Emergency Economic Stabilization Act of 2008, which is to establish the program, and then it will be the turn of the Senate.
President George W. Bush spoke to Pelosi on Saturday evening, after which the news of the agreement was welcomed by the White House.
"We are pleased with the progress made last night and greatly appreciate the efforts of both sides to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy," White House spokesman Tony Fratto said in a statement.
In fact, the program differs from the Bush administration’s original proposal that a total of $700 billion should be spent to buy low-quality mortgage-backed securities at once.
It is now possible to spend a maximum of half of 700 billion in the first round, so that 250 billion will be used immediately after the matter is expected to be decided by Congress on Monday, and the Treasury Department will buy mortgage-backed securities that are rated as low-quality, the fate of the remaining $ 100 billion will then depend on the President’s decision.
The program will be controlled by a special body, of which the chairman of the Federal Reserve Bank will also be a member.
The spending of the second half of $700 billion will depend on the next decision of Congress.
The Ministry of Finance can use a combined tactic in the sense of the law: it can simultaneously buy low-quality loans, mortgages and securities secured by mortgages, or other "poisonous" loans.
The purchase can take place within the framework of auctions and directly, said the competent representatives of the Ministry.
The legal norm will allow the firms concerned to participate in an insurance program in which the Treasury Department provides them with a guarantee for funds that are cause for concern, for which the companies will then pay a price corresponding to the amount of the expected damages.
As Henry Paulson said, the law provides the necessary resources to meet the urgent demands of the US financial system to spend up to $ 700 billion, whether it is a large-scale purchase of bad funds, their insurance or to prevent the systemic risk associated with the collapse of one of the major monetary institutions.
"We will take the necessary steps to be ready to implement the law as soon as it is signed," he added.
On the contrary, bank bosses who are in trouble and waiting for the state’s help can count on the government to cut their severance pay – which is simply called “golden parachute” in overseas slang.
Their payments will only be limited in certain cases and will depend on the type of assistance provided by the Ministry.
The restriction essentially means that if the ministry makes purchases as part of an auction, a tax surcharge will be imposed on gold parachutes unless the bank’s deceased directors are sent straight to retirement.
In the case of the direct purchase of low-quality loans, the government will aggressively intervene in order to ensure that the money for management is not exaggerated.
It should be added that the existing contracts on gold parachutes will not change, the restriction applies only to new contracts, which should be an additional incentive to participate in the programme.
“This is the first time in U.S. history that there will be a legal restriction on the remuneration of CEOs,” House Financial Services Committee chairman Barney Frank said in a statement.
In addition, the State will have the right to acquire a stake in the banks participating in the programme, which will reduce the risk to the taxpayer, because once the economy and the rescued bank get back on their feet, they can also profit from this transaction.
The bill stipulates that in the next five years, the president must submit a proposal to Congress setting out how taxpayers can recover expected losses from the financial sector.
Of course, there were voices on both sides expressing doubts about the plan.
“This is not what the American people asked us to do, because taxpayer dollars are not going to protect us,” California Republican Congressman Darrell Issa said.
His Ohio Democratic colleague Mary Kaptur believes that it was precisely those responsible for the collapse of Wall Street who urged the adoption of the provisions.
Industrial prices continued to rise
Domestic sales prices in the industry increased by 0.1% in August 2008 compared to the previous month, compared to 12.9 percent in August 2007, the Central Statistical Office announced.
Export sales prices in the industry were 1.1 percent higher than in July 2008, decreasing by 3.9 percent year-on-year.
As a cause of changes in domestic and export prices compared to the previous month, production prices in industry were 0.7% higher, increasing by 3.2% year-on-year.
Domestic sales prices in the industry increased only minimally, by 0.1%, compared to the previous month.
Also, domestic sales prices in the manufacturing sectors increased slightly, by 0.1%, compared to July.
The largest increase in prices took place in August 2008 in the leather and footwear industry (2.8%), mainly due to the monthly increase in prices in the production of bags and saddlery products by 4.6% and footwear production by 2.5%, respectively.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical raw materials caused a significant monthly price increase in the chemical materials and products industry (1.6 percent).
Prices declined in the oil processing industry (1.4 percent), in the production of electrical machinery and equipment (0.9 percent), as well as - to a minimum extent - in the woodworking sector (0.1 percent).
Prices in the field of paper production and publishing and printing activities have not changed.
In other sectors of the manufacturing industry, we measured price increases in the range of 0.2 - 0.9 percent.
In the production and distribution of electricity, gas and water, which has a high weight in the domestic sales of industry, prices increased by 0.3% in August, mainly due to the continuing impact of the officially determined increase in gas prices taking place from 1 July.
In the twelve-month comparison of domestic sales in individual sectors of the manufacturing industry, prices increased the most in the professional sector of oil processing (32.4 percent).
In the metalworking sector 13.2% was observed, in the production of food products, beverages and tobacco products, which has a decisive weight, followed by an 11% increase in prices.
Prices fell in textiles and textile products (2.5 per cent) and electrical machinery and equipment (0.3 per cent).
In other sectors of the manufacturing industry, the price growth rate ranged between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
Overall, prices in the manufacturing industry increased by 10.2 percent last year.
Prices in the production and distribution of electricity, gas and water exceeded prices from the previous year by 18.7%.
In August, domestic sales showed the highest monthly price increase (0.7 percent) in the sectors involved in the production of tangible assets.
In the consumer goods sector, prices increased by 0.3%, while in the energy and further processing sectors, prices remained unchanged compared to the previous month.
The largest increase in prices compared to the same month of the previous year was observed in August 2008 in the energy processing and further processing sectors (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods sectors, we measured a price increase of 6.8 percent, while for tangible assets, prices fell by 1.4 percent.
Export sales prices of industrial products, measured in forints, increased by 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month, down 3.9 percent in 12-month comparison.
Our domestic currency weakened by 1.7 percent against the euro in one month, by 7.1 percent against the dollar, by 7.5 percent against the euro in August 2007 and by 15.9 percent against the dollar.
