This can be explained, according to Russian observers, by the prosperity and stability of the country led by Alexander Lukashenko, but according to the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), by the illegalities that occurred during the counting of votes.
The OSCE, which sent 450 observers from 43 countries, did not recognize the election.
Although the 110-member legislature of the 10-million-strong country has been lacking opposition for well over a decade, the opposition grouped under the name of the United Democratic Forces (ODS) before yesterday's election seriously hoped that Lukashenko, who retained a constitutional change in the elections with a controversial turnout in 2006, would re-elect his president several times in 2006 and for the fourth time.
The ODS also dropped the boycott that had been contemplated.
Against the backdrop of the opposition’s expectation was that Russia’s economically increasingly dependent Belarus – which took a loan to mitigate the impact of Russia’s ever-expensive natural gas imports and also contributed to Beltransgaz, which owns gas pipelines passing through the country, to get into Russian hands – wished politically to improve relations with Luoru as anti-government with the European Union.
It has previously pointed out that in evaluating the election campaign, the OSCE emphasized positive developments rather than shortcomings - for example, the ban on the candidacy of a third of opposition candidates.
However, Monday's flash report of the OSCE already had reservations about the campaign, during which opposition candidates could not appear in the press, in particular, the fact that the opposition could not be present at the vote count.
At the same time, according to the opposition, there is an improvement in the political system: political prisoners have been released, and Minsk is willing to engage in minor confrontations with Moscow, while still refusing to recognize the breakaway South Ossetia and Abkhazia from Georgia, although Russia, with which Belarus forms a two-month state, considers Belarus as a landlocked state.
"We have taken two steps forward and one step back, but the most important thing is that the dialogue between Belarus and the EU has started," Alexander Milinkevich told our newspaper.
According to the opposition candidate from the 2006 presidential election, it is desirable that it should remain so, despite the fact that "the power was afraid to let a single member of the opposition into the insignificant parliament".
Looking at the results of the opposition, it does not plan protest actions, but rather tries to deliver its message to voters about the need for economic reforms.
"Of course, we have a lot of problems with this, we have to print opposition papers in Russia, the local authorities put obstacles in the distribution, but I still see that more and more people are supporting the change, even among the elderly," Milinkevich said, pointing out that the Lukashenko regime, which considers the creation of social security as its greatest success, does not consider the strata as correct or officially the most supported.
"Due to the country's debt and the growing trade deficit, it is only a matter of time before the social security 'provoking silence of the cemetery' collapses," Milinkevich said.
Unlike the opposition politician, Russian observers rated the election as democratic.
The head of the CIS mission, Sergey Lebedev, told Russia’s Ria Novosti news agency that “people don’t believe in words but in deeds”, so the absence of opposition is nothing but proof of the maturity of the Belarusian voters.
