Work Accidents, Napolitano: "Resolute Prevention"
Every day, there are 2,500 accidents at work in Italy, three people die and twenty-seven remain permanently disabled.
The Inail figures confirm that in 2007 we had about 1,200 deaths from work-related accidents.
These values testify to the seriousness of the phenomenon, which remains one of the main causes of death and causes almost twice the number of deaths compared to murders.
To renew the attention of institutions, social media and information about this dramatic problem, Anmil celebrates today in all Italian regions the 58th National Day of Victims of Work-related Accidents, set for the second Sunday in October.
“The disturbing data disseminated by Anmil and the same tragic news of these days confirm the importance of the issue of occupational safety,” President Giorgio Napolitano confirmed in a message sent to President Anmil by the National Association for the Disabled and Disabled for Work, Pietro Mercandelli.
The Head of State expresses his deep admiration for the continuous joint efforts to ensure safety in the workplace, the protection of injured workers, the assistance to the families of the victims and the participation of public opinion.
“Naturally, an outraged ‘enough’ was raised, sincerely shared in the face of tragedies that, by their scale, stir up turmoil in the media and public participation, but everyday reality again offers us dramatic cases, even repeating itself in its dynamics.”
Napolitano does not hide that "there is undoubtedly a resource problem: it is crucial to invest in training and awareness.
The numerous initiatives put in place in the field of education are of particular importance in order to raise awareness among young people facing the world of work.
It is necessary to draw attention to this phenomenon, not to give up because of its disturbing social significance, to apply and improve legislative norms.
Chamber President Gianfranco Fini, for his part, underlined "how the phenomenon of death from an occupational accident creates an absolutely critical social state, how it offends the conscience of each of us and forces all institutions to make convincing efforts towards the necessary end of this state."
"As for the data on occupational accidents, they seem to be showing some positive turnover, but this does not deny that the number of deaths from occupational accidents is alarming anyway," President Anmila Pietro Mercandelli remarked.
“We don’t want this ‘reducing effort’ to lead to less attention, because the moment the attention stops, tragedy breaks out.
“In general, we believe that too little is being done to stop the problem of accidents, and there are many activities that can have an impact on this problem.
It is necessary, in our opinion, to increase controls and inspections, but also to intervene more strongly in the field of training of workers, right from school age."
"More efforts are needed," he added, "in terms of communication and participation of public opinion.
But above all, there is a need for a greater sense of responsibility on the part of employers towards a phenomenon that represents an exceptional social phenomenon.
Mercandelli said it was a “progressive degeneration of the levels of entitlement to compensation envisaged for labour victims” and the “deferral of supportive care” that the system has been getting into in recent years.
“The goal is to give back the insurance guarantee to the worker,” he added, “because the fate of those who hurt themselves must not depend on spontaneity or the gift from time to time by the legislator.”
Mp3 Players Charged, Puts Hearing at Risk
Listening to loud music for long periods of time and using portable music devices such as Mp3 players can cause permanent hearing damage.
According to a statement published today by the European Commission, which in an official report disseminated in Brussels quotes the opinion of the Committee on Science on the health risks that have recently arisen and have been identified (Crseri) Eu.
“From this scientific opinion, we read in the notes, it follows that 5-10% of those who listen to music using portable music devices for at least five years, weekly for more than an hour a day and keep the device at high volumes risk permanent hearing loss.”
“It worries me that such a large number of young people, who often use portable music devices and mobile phones at high acoustic levels, can unknowingly damage their hearing in an irreparable way,” admits Meglena Kuneva.
"Scientific findings," the leader continues, "implie a clear risk and need to respond swiftly.
Most importantly, we need to encourage consumers and make this information public.
We must continue to re-examine existing control systems in the light of this scientific finding to make them fully effective and keep pace with the new technology.”
Brussels has asked the Independent Scientific Committee to investigate the problem due to the high use of portable musical instruments and the growing number of young people exposed to noise of this origin.
"Scientists - concluded the EU executive - confirm the need to worry and now the European Commission is examining, together with other members and parties who have raised the issue, what measures could possibly be put in place to better protect children and young people from exposure to noise caused by portable musical instruments and similar devices."
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable musical instruments to 100 dB, but there are growing concerns about hearing damage that may be caused by overexposure to similar forms of noise.
It is possible to greatly limit these damages by looking for solutions such as reducing the level and duration of exposure.
In its opinion, the Scientific Committee of the EU states that users of portable musical instruments, if they use loud music (more than 89 decibels) for only five hours a week, will exceed the current limits corresponding to the maximum allowed noise at the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for a long time risk permanent hearing loss after five years.
This problem should affect 5-10% of users of such devices and their number can be estimated between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
