Elites in Danger
This phenomenon was manifested a few days ago, when the House of Representatives voted against the $700 billion bailout plan presented by the White House: a significant proportion of Americans were more interested and interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the economy.
This is confirmed by yesterday’s New York Times, which informs us that the current crisis is dividing the Republican Party, increasingly divided between its old East Coast soul, the milder one, accommodating to federal institutions and the business community, and its new soul, which, on the contrary, is conservative, hostile to the “those in Washington” and the middle part, and to the world of finance.
The soul that arrogantly manifested itself in the vote I spoke of at the beginning.
But this matter just quoted is but an example of the changes, the great changes, which the current economic earthquake already shows: not only in the United States, but throughout the West, and perhaps not only here.
Both in the U.S. and in Europe, this crisis seems to act as an accelerator for phenomena that have been in incubation for a long time, that are solidifying in the new climate and finally coming to light.
The first of these phenomena is the re-actualization, the extraordinary recovery of the market, the double category of State-Power in relation to a certain re-nationalization of the economy.
The crisis is indeed a crisis of banking and financial institutions, which, of course, have strong ties abroad, but in which the budgets of people and families living in one country, in one state, are mainly involved.
This has at the same time created a political problem for those who govern it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of people and families, who are, among other things, voters.
In short, the crisis appears to be economically global, but politically almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems to be substantially out of the question or to have little to say: the European Union, which, as always, is divided between different interests and different national strategies, and which is unable to decide on a single common political line, has given clear evidence.
And so everyone is waiting for the intervention of the government of each individual state, the rescue plans, the market recovery, the new rules and, most importantly, the distribution of funds: at the moment when we get into distress, only the states have the economic means, the amount of financial resources to be able to try to put everything in order.
And they also have the necessary means and powers to use them: two sources of immense value, under certain circumstances, which perhaps no market and no international organization will ever be able to dispose of to a similar degree.
This new emphasis, which the crisis places on the state-national element, is, moreover, in full accord with the ever-increasing importance which the recent economic progress is trying to attribute to one factor closely connected with it: territorial affiliation.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we had entered the realms of the grid, increasingly sophisticated technology, imetrial, while we were convinced that global finance was already destined to rule the world, we suddenly realized that our future, on the other hand, would have to deal with such little intangible things as oil, water, grain, etc.
All things, who would have said it, can be transported from one place on earth to another, but in any case they are connected, absolutely, to a bounded space, a territory.
So whoever becomes their ruler certainly has far more cards in his sleeve than whoever isn't, and whoever has the bad luck of living in a place without grain, without oil, and without water.
I come to the second novelty, which, however, predicts a breakthrough.
Whoever speaks of territory, of state, of government, inevitably speaks of politics, that is, of leadership.
Given the economic crisis, two convergent phenomena appear to be forming.
On the one hand, the realization that there is an objective need for authoritarian leadership, a request for someone who can grasp the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit against existing leadership, especially economic ones, which turned out to be equally unsatisfactory and full of dark places.
And together, something even deeper and in a sense disturbing: discredit, impatience, a sense of incompetence and absence that seeks to dominate the entire ruling class in more and more Western countries.
It seems, in fact, that convictions are spreading more and more among the broad masses of the population, rather than that their actions are the same as the ideas of the hitherto popular elite, as their way of feeling and being, as their culture in the true sense of the word, that the elite has already surpassed their time and is indifferent to the opinions of the majority.
The demand for leadership, in short, feeds one branch of the right from the underground, but the strong movement for the elimination of the ruling classes and the traditional political order is manifested in sudden electoral "resistance" or in unexpected changes in collective moods in the last and most recent time, from the conservative rise of the British to the Congress in Great Britain, to the Congress in Lausanne and Bavaria.
We have the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their ceremonies, their newspapers, their accredited intelligence, someone would say their format, have increasing difficulties to understand, that is, to represent, which, not from today, is being created in the deep strata of Western societies, and that the economic crisis is once again strengthening, expanding, potentially going too far.
Before that, it would be exaggerated to speak of a permanent "mass rebellion".
But we certainly can't say that it means keeping our eyes open.
Super glue for walking on walls
Overcome the laws of gravity thanks to super glue and in the future walk on the walls as Spiderman.
This is the object of various American research centers, and now a team of four institutes has come very close to it.
The scientists managed to keep a 100-kilogram body glued to a vertical wall using a sticker of only 2.5 square centimeters.
STUDY – The American journal Science has published the findings of some researchers at the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material, invented by a team of researchers, is a development of existing materials that use a special carbon structure called carbon dwarf tubes.
“The glue base can be imagined as a series of tubes laid out as a stack of spaghetti,” explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
The scientists were inspired by the gecko's legs, covered with microscopic hairs that allow the animal to ensure perfect adhesion.
Tests conducted on various materials, such as glass, Teflon and glass paper, showed that the new adhesive is ten times stronger than the feet of these reptiles and at the same time "simply peels off from the wall", explains Liming Dai, a researcher at the Faculty of Engineering at Dayton University.
- "This material could be useful as a temporary glue" adds Liming Dai.
Perhaps to walk on walls like Spiderman? Perhaps yes, but researchers are thinking of a far less fascinating use as a connection of electrical devices, because dwarf carbon pipes are conductors of heat and electricity.
Other applications could relate to aerospace engineering.
So far, no superheroes.
FURTHER RESEARCH – The University of Berkley, California, is also researching a new adhesive.
In an article in the American Chemical Society, Californian scientists presented a microfiber-formed adhesive as hair that cleans itself of dust by moving it over the surface to still retain perfect adhesion.
Medications: never with juices
Beware of grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
If you take these drinks, which are consumed mainly in the summer, because they are refreshing and full of vitamins, along with some life-saving drugs, their intake changes the potency with serious consequences for health.
In order for David Bailey, a professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, to highlight the risks of both ready-made and fresh juices combined with the intake of certain medications, the 263rd National Meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia is raising a new alarm effect: one glass of grapefruit, orange and apple juice is enough to reduce the risk of their health.
Grapefruit juice has already been accused of being responsible for increasing to toxic levels the effects of certain antiarrhythmic drugs, antibiotics, anxiolytics, antihistamines and neurological drugs.
The Italian Medical Agency itself announced this in a bulletin two years ago, urging doctors and patients not to underestimate the dangers of this mixture and to be careful what they drink if they take medications such as Diazepam or Methadone.
Not just grapefruit – According to experts, orange and apple juice also contain substances that suppress drugs.
A long list of effects muted by grapefruit and other juices.
Michele Carruba, Director of Pharmacology at the State University of Milan, said: "Such discoveries are usually immediately reported to various international and national pharmacy agencies, which will eventually arrange and exchange information instructions for medicines.
