Farewell to the old cinema Paradiso, the cities are canceling historic halls
The cinematographic historical halls are closed in favour of the Multiplex.
“A city without cinemas is like a blind city, like a face without eyes.”
The painting offered by director Giuseppe Tornatoro successfully documents what is happening in the large Italian urban centers, as well as in rural towns.
The process of restricting cinemas, the birth of large multi-salaries in the suburbs and the subsequent disappearance of monosalas in the central zones of cities is one of the events that seems inevitable and irreversible, but also has all the features of a real cultural crime.
"It's like losing a friend, an acquaintance, with whom we shared a piece of the journey and a lot of emotions," feels the director of New Cinema Paradiso, a film that twenty years ago won Tornator an Oscar and a big jury award in Cannes, and who told the story of a life and a life of a villager.
The figures obtained by Anec, the main association of operators, speak clearly: in the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed their doors, and the highest bill was paid mainly by halls in the most important cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by closures, Emilia-Romagna comes first with a loss of 82 cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And the proof that the first responsible for their disappearance is the onset of the multiplex is precisely these three Italian regions, which have registered the highest number of new cinema multisales: 195 more canvases in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 more in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
“The Italian approach has evolved irrationally,” says Paolo Protti, president of Anecu, “it is useful to create new structures, but it would be necessary to guarantee that the existing ones will survive, because when one cinema in the city closes, not all of its visitors are willing to move to the multiplex.
Then let us not even talk about the insufficient subsidy to the fund for the benefit of operators: the previous national debt is about EUR 10 million.
From a moral and ethical point of view, it is a disgrace that the government does not respect existing laws.
Between 16 and 18 million euros per year would be needed to support the sector.”
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city concerned with closures and which decided to find a way out by signing a protocol between the village and Aneca, the first of its kind in Italy to protect and promote small cinemas both in historical centers and in the suburbs.
Among the planned standards are the steps of tax relief in favor of operators and the benefits for the audience in terms of mobility: viewers will be able to drive into the zone with limited traffic and will have special prices to stop and in some parking lots.
“I like this initiative,” says Giuseppe Tornatore, “and I hope other cities will follow Bologna’s example by introducing other measures.”
However, it is certain that in order to stand up to the great power of the multiplex, traditional halls must improve the quality of sound and image, because today's audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a topic that has always been important: the closure of the Super Cinema in Bagheria, instead of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to found the “New Paradiso Cinema” that I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass in front of the already closed Rialto or Quirinale in Nazionale Street, where I have shared so much emotion that I do not have to look at the inscriptions blackened by dust, I turn to the other side.
